## Migration: `BackgroundProcessor` → .NET 8

### Pattern Classification

| Usage | Pattern | Replacement |
|-------|---------|-------------|
| `while (_running)` loop | Cancellable work loop | `CancellationToken` |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | Control flow cleanup | `catch (OperationCanceledException)` |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | Continue after abort | `token.IsCancellationRequested` check |
| `Thread.Abort()` in `Stop()` | Force termination | `CancellationTokenSource.Cancel()` |

### Why This Breaks on .NET 8

`Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` — it **does not abort the thread**. Your `Stop()` method will crash and the blocked worker will hang forever.

### Migrated Code

```csharp
public class BackgroundProcessor : IDisposable
{
    private Thread? _workerThread;
    private CancellationTokenSource? _cts;

    public void Start()
    {
        _cts = new CancellationTokenSource();
        _workerThread = new Thread(() => ProcessLoop(_cts.Token));
        _workerThread.IsBackground = true;
        _workerThread.Start();
    }

    private void ProcessLoop(CancellationToken token)
    {
        while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            try
            {
                var item = GetNextItem(token); // pass token so blocking calls can wake up
                ProcessItem(item, token);
            }
            catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)
            {
                // Clean up partial work — mirrors the old ThreadAbortException block
                RollbackCurrentTransaction();
                // No ResetAbort needed — we control whether to continue or exit.
                // The loop condition will exit naturally.
            }
            finally
            {
                FlushBuffers();
            }
        }
    }

    public void Stop()
    {
        if (_cts is null || _workerThread is null)
            return;

        _cts.Cancel(); // signal cooperative cancellation

        // Wait up to 5 seconds for graceful shutdown
        if (!_workerThread.Join(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5)))
        {
            // Thread didn't stop — it's stuck in uncooperative code.
            // Log a warning; you cannot force-kill a managed thread in .NET 8.
            Console.Error.WriteLine("Worker thread did not exit within timeout.");
        }
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        Stop();
        _cts?.Dispose();
    }
}
```

### Key Changes Explained

1. **`volatile bool _running` → `CancellationToken`** — The token is thread-safe and can also wake up blocking calls. The bool couldn't do that.

2. **`Thread.Abort()` → `_cts.Cancel()`** — Cooperative signal instead of injecting an exception from outside.

3. **`ThreadAbortException` → `OperationCanceledException`** — The `when (token.IsCancellationRequested)` guard prevents catching unrelated OCEs.

4. **`Thread.ResetAbort()` → removed** — Not needed. You control the loop; it exits via the `while` condition.

5. **`Thread.Sleep(2000)` → `_workerThread.Join(timeout)`** — Actually waits for the thread instead of hoping.

6. **`IDisposable`** — `CancellationTokenSource` owns timers/callbacks and must be disposed.

### Critical Pitfall: `GetNextItem()` Must Accept the Token

If `GetNextItem()` blocks (e.g., on a queue or I/O), cancellation **will not interrupt it** unless you pass the token through. This was the whole reason the old code needed `Thread.Abort` — to break out of blocking calls.

```csharp
// ❌ Old: blocks forever, only Thread.Abort could break it
private object GetNextItem()
{
    return _queue.Take(); // blocking
}

// ✅ New: wakes up when cancelled
private object GetNextItem(CancellationToken token)
{
    return _queue.Take(token); // throws OperationCanceledException
}
```

If you're using `BlockingCollection<T>`, it already supports `Take(CancellationToken)`. If using `Thread.Sleep` to poll, replace with `token.WaitHandle.WaitOne(ms)`.

### Other Pitfalls

| Pitfall | What happens |
|---------|-------------|
| Not passing token to `ProcessItem` | Long-running items won't respond to cancellation until they finish |
| Catching `OperationCanceledException` and swallowing it silently | Hides bugs — always log or propagate |
| Forgetting to dispose `CancellationTokenSource` | Leaks timers and registered callbacks |
| Assuming `Cancel()` stops the thread immediately | It only works at the next checkpoint that checks the token |
